The '''Prissani''' or '''Pyritzans''' ({{lang-pl|Pyrzyczanie}}) were a [[Pomerania during the Early Middle Ages|medieval tribe in Pomerania]]. They were first mentioned as "Prissani" with 70 civitas by the [[Bavarian Geographer]], ca. 845.<ref name=RGA261>Johannes Hoops, Herbert Jankuhn, Heinrich Beck, Reallexikon der germanischen Altertumskunde Band 23, Walter de Gruyter, 2003, p.261, {{ISBN|3-11-017535-5}}</ref> They are associated with the [[Pomeranians (Slavic tribe)|Pomeranians]], and were based in the lower [[Oder]] region around the modern town of [[Pyrzyce]] (Pyritz).<ref name=Piskorski30>Jan M Piskorski, Pommern im Wandel der Zeiten, p.30, {{ISBN|83-906184-8-6}} {{OCLC|43087092}}</ref> The mention in the Bavarian Geographer is the only written record referring to the tribe.<ref name=Piskorski30/>
In the late 10th century, the [[Piast Poland|Polish dukes]] [[Mieszko I]] and [[Bolesław I Chrobry]] subdued parts of [[Pomerania]], but did not succeed to subdue the lower [[Oder]] region.<ref name=Piskorski31>Jan M Piskorski, Pommern im Wandel der Zeiten, p.31, {{ISBN|83-906184-8-6}} {{OCLC|43087092}}</ref> In 1121/22, the [[Piast Poland|Polish duke]] [[Bolesław III Wrymouth]] conquered the area along with the [[Duchy of Pomerania]] under [[Wartislaw I, Duke of Pomerania|Wartislaw I]].<ref name=Piskorski36>Jan M Piskorski, Pommern im Wandel der Zeiten, p.36, {{ISBN|83-906184-8-6}} {{OCLC|43087092}}</ref> The tribe was subsequently [[Conversion of Pomerania|Christianized]], missionary [[Otto of Bamberg]] celebrated the first mass baptism in [[Pyrzyce]].<ref name=Piskorski36/> A separate tribal identity, if upheld so far, vanished when it was integrated in the [[Duchy of Pomerania]].
